The genus 

Rosa

L. (
Rosaceae
) is composed of more than 100 wild species and tens of thousands of modern rose cultivars (

). In addition to be famous ornamental plants, rose flowers are rich in essential oil and other bioactive constituents such as ellagitannins, flavonoids and phenolic acids (

). Therefore, they are widely used in food, cosmetics and pharmaceutical fields. 

Rosa hugonis
Hemsl. Is

a perennial shrub widely distributed in many provinces in western and northern 
China
(

). The fresh flowers of 

R. hugonis

contain valuable volatile oil which smells sweet and fragrant, while the fruits of this plant rich in nutrients can be eaten and brewed (

; 

). Also, several carotenoids were reported from the yellow petals of this resource (M¨arki-Fischer and 

).

With the increase of human life expectancy, more and more people, especially the elderly, are suffering from neurodegenerative diseases such as Parkinson’ s, Alzheimer’ s and senile dementia (

; 

). At present, several chemosynthetic drugs with various side effects are mainly used for the treatment of cognitive deficits and memory loss related to these diseases (

). Also, 

Ginkgo biloba

L., folium extract as a natural medicine was confirmed to be effective and safe in treating mild cognitive impairment and Alzheimer’ s disease and had been approved by European Medicines Agency (

). Thus, searching for alternatives from natural resources with better neuroprotective activities and less adverse effects is a promising direction. As a continuous study of our research team and collaborators to screen undescribed neuroprotective candidates from natural plants (

; 

), we found the 70% ethanol extracts of the flowers of 

R. hugonis

exhibited moderate neuroprotective activity (
Table S1
). However, to the best of our knowledge, detailed phytochemical investigations on this species have not been

Compound 1 , a yellow amorphous powder, had the molecular formula of C 28 H 24 O 13 based on its HRESIMS at m/z 591.1109 [M +Na] + in positive ion mode. The IR spectrumn of 1 showed characteristic absorption bands for hydroxyl ( 3421 cm 1 ), double bonds ( 1608 cm 1 ) and an O-glycosidic group ( 1079 cm 1 ). The UV spectrum of 1 demonstrated absorption bands at λ max 251 and 368 nm , suggesting that compound 1 was a flavonoid. The 1 H NMR data of 1 ( Table 1 ) presented the proton signals at δ H 8.10 (2H, d, J =8.7 Hz), δ H 7.20 (2H, d, J =8.7 Hz), δ H 6.47 (1H, brs), δ H 6.20 (1H, brs) and δ H 5.07 (1H, d, J =7.1 Hz), which were in good accordance with those of kaempferol-4 ′ -O-β- Dglucopyranoside (
). The 1 H NMR and 13 C NMR spectra of 1 ( Tables 1 and 2 ) also showed two doublet signals at δ H 7.84 (2H, d, J = 8.6 Hz) and δ H 6.88 (2H, d, J =8.6 Hz) and δ C 165.4, δ C 162.2, δ C 131.5, δ C 120.3 and δ C 115.4, respectively, indicating the presence of a p -hydroxybenzoyl group in 1 (
). Acid hydrolysis of 1 afforded kaempferol, p -hydroxybenzoic acid and glucose, which were compared by co-TLC and HPLC with the authentic samples. Moreover, the glucose moiety was determined to be in β -D-glucose form by measuring its optical rotation and inferring from the large coupling constant (7.2 Hz) of the anomeric proton. The linkages between kaempferol, glucose and p -hydroxybenzoic acid were determined by the key long-range correlations from δ H 5.07 (H-1 of Glc) to δ C 158.2 (C-4 ′ of kaempferol unit), and from δ H 4.59, 4.18 (H-6 of Glc) to δ C 165.4 (C-7 of p -hydroxybenzoyl unit) ( Fig. 2 ). By extensive analysis of the 1 H-NMR, 13 C-NMR, DEPT, 1 H– 1 H COSY) HSQC, and HMBC data, the structure of compound 1 was ulteriorly defined as kaempferol 4 ′ - O -(6 ′′ - O -p -hydroxybenzoyl)- β -D-glucopyranoside ( Fig. 1 ), named hugonisflavonoid A.

