Parkinson’ s disease (PD) is one of the most common neurodegenerative movement disorder, where oxidative stress appears to be an important element in PD. 6-OHDA could induce intracellular ROS overproduction and was often used in drug screening for Parkinson’ s disease models in vitro (
;
;
). As shown in Table S1 , compounds 5 , 6 , 13–16 , 18–19 , 32 , 36–38 , 40–41 , 43–45 presented significant activities. Nevertheless, many of these compounds showed remarkable ability to promote cell proliferation. In order to eliminate the effects of cell proliferation, compound 5 , which had a novel chemical structure and exhibited relatively good activity, was selected for further investigation of its inhibitory effect on 6-OHDA-induced toxicity in PC12 cells. As shown in Fig. 3A , the cell viability was increased from 49.83% to 72.91%, 94.78%, 91.76%, 103.08% and 110.67%, respectively. When the concentration of compound 5 was 20 μM or less, there was almost no effect on cell viability ( Fig. 3B ). Therefore, the concentrations used in subsequent studies were 20 μM or lower. As shown in Fig. 3C , the cell numbers were reduced and attached cells were round and shrunken in 6-OHDA-- treated group. Pretreatment with compound 5 restored the changes in cell number and morphology.

Oxidative stress, defined as the overproduction of ROS, could cause alterations in proteins, lipids, DNA, glycogen and disrupt cellular homeostasis (
;
). Previous studies suggested that excessive ROS contributed to dopaminergic neuronal cell loss and pathophysiology of disorders in PD patients (
). The antioxidant enzymes, such as SOD and CAT, are the key enzymes in body system to protect against oxidative stress (
). As shown in Fig. 4A , the exposure of PC12 cells to 6-OHDA induced a marked increase of the cell fluorescence intensity in comparison to vehicle group. However, pretreatment with compound 5 induced a significant decrease of ROS levels. As shown in Fig. 4B and C , treatment of PC12 cells with 6-OHDA for 6 h significantly decreased the activities of SOD and CAT. However, pretreatment with compound 5 dramatically minimized the 6-OHDA-induced changes in antioxidant enzyme activities. These results suggested that the neuroprotective effect of compound 5 might be mediated by antioxidant defense mechanism.

PI3K/Akt is an important signaling pathway that controls many cellular processes, including cell division, autophagy, survival, and differentiation (

). Previous investigations have reported that natural products with protective activities against 6-OHDA-induced neurotoxicity may be mediated through the activation of PI3K/Akt/GSK3β signaling pathway, suggesting that the activation of GSK3β should be an important target (

; 

). We therefore examined the phosphorylated levels of PDK1, Akt, and G3K-3β. As shown in 
Fig. 5
, the phosphorylated levels of PDK1, Akt, and G3K-3β were decreased compared with the control group. Compound 
5
pretreatment significantly alleviated the declines of these three phosphorylated proteins.

